@PhilWalmsley4 @drsebheaven @InvictaOrtho @theartfu1doctor Well it is interesting on philosophy of conversion- some will go to a longer revision type stem- redapt is commonly bandied around. I just use a standard exeter
@drsebheaven @InvictaOrtho @theartfu1doctor Allows controlled collapse like a DHS. Otherwise it can spin. I’ve seen a nail catastrophically fail when they forgot the set screw

@NitinKimmatkar @InvictaOrtho @theartfu1doctor Unless some sort of metastatic deposit in a frail patient there is no chance I am cementing through a nail. As an arthroplasty surgeon this screams potential nightmare at me

@InvictaOrtho @theartfu1doctor We have trauma centres and more and more “full time” trauma surgeons. In the most part we do as much trauma as we do elective surgery. 95+% is managed in house in most places with some stuff transferred elsewhere- pelvis/some periarticular stuff. Poly trauma should bypass to MTC
@InvictaOrtho @theartfu1doctor Maybe in North America. Can’t see it disappearing in my consultant career. I’d be very surprised if it did. It’s part of our core curriculum.
@InvictaOrtho @theartfu1doctor How many of your short nails do you lock? Will you let a standard IT collapse like a DHS?

@InvictaOrtho @theartfu1doctor Whilst that’s true. It doesn’t mean it’s 100% destined to fail either.

@Dr_Stambough @depurhro @ExeterHipUnit @EdinburghKnee You need to be able to anatomically reduce the fracture and the bone cement interface has to be solid. It has a lower re-operation rate and a lower dislocation rate that a revision hip.
